Hi Maura,
Anne Kasmar, MD, MSc is an Infectious Disease=96trained physician-scientist=
 with over 15 years of experience spanning academia, global health philanth=
ropy, and biotech. She is currently Senior Vice President, Global Franchise=
 Head, Immunology & Infection at Parexel, where she leads a global team of =
20 physicians and directs strategy and delivery across the combined Immunol=
ogy and Infectious Diseases franchise. Prior to that, she built and led Par=
exel=92s ID & Vaccines group, serving as a key medical and scientific advis=
or to biotech and pharmaceutical clients.
Anne is attracted to this opportunity because of the intersection this role=
 can provide with her experience in networking, science, and skillset. Anne=
 has a very deep-rooted network in immunology, having worked 9 years at the=
 bench at BWH in Boston and also being a member of the American Association=
 of Immunologists. She thinks this role can benefit from her skillset at Pa=
rexel, Genentech, and Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation. She reviewed the web=
site and referencing common connections with a number of people on the boar=
d. She would be seeing a VP or SVP title and a base salary of $430k - $440k=
 but remains open to considering the whole package. She is based Presidio, =
CA and is open to go 3 days a week onsite in Oakland.
Anne Kasmar, MD, MSc

  *
Senior Vice President, Global Franchise Head, Immunology & Infection, Parex=
el | San Francisco, CA
  *
MD, UCSF; MSc in Immunology of Infectious Diseases, LSHTM; BA, Brown Univer=
sity
  *
15+ years of clinical and translational research experience across academia=
, philanthropy, and biotech
  *
Former Program Officer, Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation =96 managed $25M TB=
 vaccine portfolio; BioNTech collaboration lead
  *
Lead Medical Director, Genentech =96 GvHD, antibiotic programs, infectious =
disease strategy
  *
SVP, Global Franchise Head, Immunology & Infection, Parexel =96 leads team =
of 20 globally distributed physicians
  *
Experience across vaccines, biologics, and host-directed therapies for ID a=
nd immunology indications


